p:
The basic reproduction number R 0 is defined as the average number of secondary infections that results from a single infectious individual in a fully susceptible population. For the System 1, R 0 can be computed using the next-generation technique [ 5], and it results to be
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document} $$R_{0} = \left [x + q(1 - x)\right ]\beta /\gamma $$ \end{document}
. R 0 can thus be interpreted as a weighted sum of two basic reproductive numbers: the reproductive number for individuals adopting the normal behavior (namely the fraction x), i.e.,
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document} $$R_{0}^{n} = \beta /\gamma $$ \end{document}
and the reproductive number for individuals adopting the altered behavior (namely the fraction 1 − x), i.e.,
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document} $$R_{0}^{a} = q\beta /\gamma $$ \end{document}
. Therefore, R 0 depends on the fraction of individuals in the population who are currently adopting either normal or altered behavior.
